<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-GoodFitTest" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Chi-square Goodness of Fit Test</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      A chi square distribution can be used for tests concerning frequency distributions.  Such as, is the number of colors the same for each flavor in a bag of Skittles. It can also be used to see whether a frequency distribution fits a specific pattern. Suppose traffic engineer wishes to see whether accidents occur more often on some days of the week than others. When testing to see whether a frequency distribution fits a specific pattern, we can use the <term>chi-square goodness-of-fit test</term>.  
    </p>
  </introduction>

 <objectives>
  <introduction>
    <p> At the end of this section you will be able to:   </p>
  </introduction>
  <ol>
    <li> <p> Test a distribution for goodness of fit using the chi square test. </p> </li>
     <li> <p> Determine if frequencies are the same. </p>    </li>
     <li> <p> Determine if frequencies match a specific pattern. </p>    </li>
        </ol>
</objectives>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-GoodFitBasics">
  <title>Understanding the Basics</title>
<p> A chi-square test for one categorical variable is used to analyze the
  distribution of counts across categories and determine whether the observed
  frequencies differ significantly from what we would expect. In an introductory
  statistics course, this test is often used to decide whether sample data
  provide enough evidence to conclude that a population distribution does not
  follow a claimed set of proportions. By comparing observed counts to expected
  counts, the chi-square test helps us judge whether any differences are likely
  due to random chance or indicate a real difference in the population. A large chi-square statistic indicates that the observed counts differ substantially from the expected counts, suggesting that the claimed distribution may not accurately describe the population.
 </p> 
<definition xml:id="def-chi-square-goodness-of-fit">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A <term>chi-square goodness-of-fit test</term> is used to determine whether
      the distribution of a single categorical variable in a population matches a
      claimed set of proportions. The test compares the observed counts in each
      category to the expected counts that would occur if the claimed
      distribution were true. The test statistic is
      <md>\chi^2=\sum \frac{(O-E)^2}{E}</md>,
      where <m>O</m> represents an observed count and <m>E</m> represents the
      corresponding expected count. The degrees of freedom for the test are <m>df=k-1</m>, where <m>k</m> is the number of categories. 
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<p>Suppose a candy enthusiast wants to test if the number of candies for each flavor in a bag of Skittles is the same. He opens a big of skittles and collects a random sample of 100 candies and organizes them into flavors with the following results: 22 strawberry, 24 orange, 14 grape, 17 lemon, and 23 green apple. </p>
<p>If there was no difference, one would expect each flavor to have the same frequency. In this case, <m>100/5=20 </m> candies per flavor is expected. Since the frequencies for each flavor were obtained from a sample, these actual frequencies are called the <term>observed frequencies</term>. The frequencies obtained by calculations are called the <term>expected frequencies</term>. </p>
<p>The observed frequencies often differ from the expected frequencies due to sampling error. But our question is, is there a significant difference between the frequencies or is it due to chance?</p>
<p>We are going to shift how we write hypotheses. The null hypothesis is a statement indication there is no difference or no change in the frequencies while the alternative states that the frequency is different than expected. </p>
<p><m>H_0:</m> The flavor frequencies are equal.</p>
<p><m>H_a:</m> The flavor frequencies are not equal.</p>
<p>In the goodness of fit test, the degrees of freedom are equal to the number of categories minus 1. In this case, there are five flavors for <m>df=5-1=4 </m>.</p>
<p>The formula for the chi square goodness of fit test is
<md> \chi ^2 = \sum{\frac{(O-E)^2}{E}} </md> where O = observed frequencies, E = expected frequency. </p>

<p>The assumption for the chi-square test is that the data are obtained from a random sample and the expected frequency for each category must be at least 5. Because the O-E values are squared, the answer will always be positive so every test will be a right-tailed test using the chi-square distribution.</p>
<p>It is helpful to create a table with the observed frequencies, the expected counts, the difference between the observed and expected values.</p>

    <table>
      <title>Observed and Expected Counts</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Flavor</cell>
          <cell>Observed</cell>
          <cell>Expected</cell>
         <cell>Difference O-E</cell>
          <cell><m>\frac{(O-E)^2}{E}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Strawberry</cell> <cell>22</cell> <cell>20</cell><cell>2</cell> <cell><m>0.20</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Orange</cell> <cell>24</cell><cell>20</cell> <cell>4</cell> <cell><m>0.80</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Grape</cell> <cell>14</cell><cell>20</cell> <cell>-6</cell> <cell><m>1.80</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Lemon</cell> <cell>17</cell><cell>20</cell> <cell>-3</cell> <cell><m>0.45</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Green Apple</cell> <cell>23</cell><cell>20</cell> <cell>3</cell> <cell><m>0.45</m></cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>

<p>The test statistic is <m> \chi^2 = \sum{\dfrac{(O-E)^2}{E}}</m>
<md> \chi^2 = \frac{2^2}{20} + \frac{4^2}{20} + \frac{(-6)^2} {20} +\frac{(-3)^2} {20}+\frac{3^2} {20}=3.70</md></p>
<p> Since the test statistic is relatively small for chi-squared, this means it is a good fit for having an equal distribution. If the test statistic is large, that indicates there is a larger difference between the observed and the expected values. </p> 
<p> To find the p-value, we go to StatKey and under <term> Theoretical Distributions</term> select <m>\chi ^2 </m> and enter the degrees of freedom of 4, identify Right Tail, and enter the test statistic 3.70 along the bottom to get the p-value of 0.448, image below.  </p>
<figure xml:id="ChiSquareSkittles1">
            <caption>Chi-square p-value for a test statistic of 3.70</caption>
            <image source="ChiSkittles1.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription>Right tail area of 0.448 for chi=3.70.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 

<p> On the graphing calculator press [2nd] button and [VARS] to select DISTR and scroll down to <term>7: <m>\chi^2</m> cdf( </term>  then press [ENTER] to select it and then input 3.70 [,] E99 [,] 4 [)] then press [ENTER] to calculate the p-value = 0.448126. To get the EE press the [2nd] button then [,] button and then enter 99. </p>
<figure xml:id="ChiSquareSkittles2">
            <caption>Chi-square p-value from calculator</caption>
            <image source="ChiSkittles2.png" width="70%">
                <shortdescription>Right tail area of 0.4481 for chi=3.70.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 

<p>Since <m> p \gt 0.05</m> we do not reject the null hypothesis. We cannot conclude a significant difference in the number of candies for each flavor. Thus, there are approximately the same number of candies for each flavor. The chi-square test indicates it is still a good fit for having approximately equal frequencies. </p>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-GoodFitExamples">
  <title>Examples for the chi-square goodness of fit test</title>
<p> There are two main cases for the chi-square goodness of fit test that we will be investigating. 1) the frequency distribution is equal for each category or 2) it matches a specific pattern based on previous data. We will look at an example of both cases here. </p> 
<p> <term> Wildflowers</term> </p>
<p>
      A hiking enthusiast is studying whether four species of wildflowers appear in equal
      proportions along some hiking trails in Rocky Mountain National Park. After randomly selecting and identifying  <m>120</m> wildflowers, the hiker records the following observed counts:
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Observed Wildflower Counts</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Species</cell>
          <cell>Observed Count</cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Colorado Columbine</cell><cell>24</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Mountain Bluebell</cell><cell>36</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Lupine</cell><cell>31</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Yarrow</cell><cell>29</cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>\alpha = 0.05</m> significance level, test whether the four species of wildflowers are equally distributed along the hiking trails.
    </p> 
<figure xml:id="Flowers1">
            <caption>Wildflower images</caption>
            <image source="Flowers1.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription>decorative- pictures of wildflowers .</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 

<example xml:id="ex-chisquareGOF-equal-flowers">
  <title>Wildflowers</title>
   
  <statement>
<p> State the null and alternative hypotheses, verify the assumption for a chi-square test, compute the test statistic, find the p-value, and state the conclusion in context.
</p> 
  </statement>
  <solution><title> Hypotheses</title> 
    <p>
      Let the null hypothesis be that the four wildflower species are equally
      distributed. So we would expect 25% in each of the four categories.
    </p>
    <p> The null hypotheses is </p>
      <p><m>H_0:</m> The flower species are equally distributed or <m>p_1=p_2=p_3=p_4=0.25</m> </p>
     <p> And the alternative hypothesis is</p>
      <p><m>H_a:</m> The species are not equally distributed. Which means at least one of the proportions differs from 0.25.   </p>
</solution>
<solution><title>Assumptions</title>
<p> It was a random sample of flowers and there are at least 5 in each category, so we can use the chi-square distribution. </p>
</solution> 
<solution><title> Values</title>
    <p>
      Since there are 120 flowers and 4 categories, the expected count for each flower species under equal distribution is <m>\dfrac{120}{4}=30</m>.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Observed and Expected Counts</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Species</cell>
          <cell>Observed</cell>
          <cell>Expected</cell>
         <cell>Difference O-E</cell>
          <cell><m>\dfrac{(O-E)^2}{E}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell> Columbine </cell> <cell>24</cell> <cell>30</cell><cell>-6</cell> <cell><m>1.20</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell> Bluebell </cell> <cell>36</cell><cell>30</cell> <cell>6</cell> <cell><m>1.20</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell> Lupine </cell> <cell>31</cell><cell>30</cell> <cell>1</cell> <cell><m>0.033</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell> Yarrow </cell> <cell>29</cell><cell>30</cell> <cell>-1</cell> <cell><m>0.033</m></cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
</solution>
<solution><title> Good Fit Test</title> 
    <p>
      The chi-square test statistic is  <m> \chi^2 = \sum{\dfrac{(O-E)^2}{E}}</m>
<md> \chi^2 = \frac{(-6)^2}{30} + \frac{6^2}{30} + \frac{1^2} {30} +\frac{(-1)^2} {30} =2.467</md>
      <md>
        \chi^2=1.20+1.20+0.033+0.033=2.466
      </md> from the table above.
    </p>
    <p> The degrees of freedom from 4 categories is <m>df=k-1=4-1=3</m>.
    </p>
    <p> Using a chi-square distribution with 3 degrees of freedom, the
      <m>p</m>-value for a right tailed test is <m>p=0.481</m>.
    </p>
</solution>
<solution><title> Conclusion</title>
    <p>  Since <m>p=0.481 \gt 0.05</m>, we fail to reject <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is not sufficient evidence at the <m>\alpha = 0.05</m> significance level to
      conclude that the four wildflower species are not equally distributed along the hiking trails in Rocky Mountain National Park.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>
<example> <title> TI-83 Plus</title> 
<p>Note: The TI-83 Plus does not have the chi-square goodness of fit test, but we can program it to do the calculations from the lists.</p>
<p> <term>Input Data: </term>Press [STAT] button and under the EDIT menu select <term>1:Edit </term> and press [ENTER].  Input the Observed values in L1 and the Expected values in L2. </p>
<p><term>Find Sum: </term>Press [2nd] [STAT] for LIST and use the arrow twice to the right to the MATH menu across the top and select <term>5 Sum( </term> and press [ENTER] to select it.</p>
<figure xml:id="ChiFlowers2">
            <caption>Input values into calculator</caption>
            <image source="Flowers2.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription> Input values into calculator under Lists.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 

<p>We are going to program the calculator to compute the chi-square value:
You will need to add a parenthesis at the beginning since we want to square the difference in the values before dividing by the expected value for that cell. The process is [ ( ] [2nd] [1] for L1 [–] [2nd] [2] for L2 [ ) ]  [x²] [÷] [2nd] [2] for  L2 [ ) ] then press [ENTER] to perform the calculations. </p>
<figure xml:id="ChiFlowers3">
            <caption>Program calculator to find sum</caption>
            <image source="Flowers3.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription> Program calculator to find sum (L1-L2)62 divide L2.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 
 <p>
  The statistical test value is <m> \chi^2 = 2.467</m> and the degrees of freedom is 3.
 </p>
<p> To find the p-value press [2nd] button and [VARS] to select DISTR and scroll down to <term>7: <m>\chi^2</m> cdf( </term> then press [ENTER] to select it and then input 2.467 [,] E99 [,] 3 [)] then press [ENTER] to calculate the p-value = 0.48128. To get the EE press the [2nd] button then [,] button then enter 99. </p>
  <figure xml:id="ChiFlowers4">
            <caption>Calculate the p-value</caption>
            <image source="Flowers4.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription> Test value chi=2.467 and p-value=0.481.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 
 </example> 

<example> <title> TI-84 GOF-test</title> 
<p><term>Input Data: </term> Press [STAT] button and under the EDIT menu select <term>1:Edit </term> and press [ENTER]. Input the Observed values in L1 and the Expected values in L2. </p>
<p> Press the [STAT] button and under the TESTS menu select <term>D: GOF-Test</term> and press [ENTER] to select it. </p>
<figure xml:id="ChiFlowers5">
            <caption>Input values into calculator</caption>
            <image source="Flowers5.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription> Input values into calculator under Lists.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 

<p> Identify where the data is located, Observed in L1 and Expected in L2. Identify the degrees of freedom of 3  and then scroll to Calculate and press [ENTER]. </p>
<figure xml:id="ChiFlowers6">
            <caption>GOF-Test value and p-value</caption>
            <image source="Flowers6.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription> Test value chi=2.467 and p-value=0.481.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 

<p> The chi-square test value is <m> \chi ^2 = 2.4667</m> and the p-value is <m>p=0.4813</m> and it will list the contributions for each category. </p> 
<p> If you select <term> Draw</term> instead it will graph the chi-square distribution and identified the chi-square test statistic 2.4667 and p-value p=0.4813. </p>
<figure xml:id="ChiFlowers7">
            <caption>Chi-square distribution with p-value</caption>
            <image source="Flowers7.png" width="60%">
                <shortdescription> Test value chi=2.467 and p-value=0.481.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 

</example> 

<p> <term> Intersection Accidents</term> </p>
<p>
      A traffic safety researcher wants to test whether the distribution of
      accidents among four types of intersections matches a previously reported
      pattern. Past transportation data suggest that <m>20\%</m> of intersection
      accidents occur at roundabouts, <m>30\%</m> at stop-sign intersections,
      <m>35\%</m> at traffic-light intersections, and <m>15\%</m> at other types
      of intersections. To investigate whether a more recent sample follows this
      distribution, the researcher records <m>400</m> intersection accidents and
      classifies each one by intersection type.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Observed Accident Counts by Intersection Type</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Intersection Type</cell>
          <cell>Observed Count</cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Roundabout</cell><cell>68</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Stop Sign</cell><cell>134</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Traffic Light</cell><cell>146</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Other</cell><cell>52</cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the population
      distribution of accidents differs from the reported distribution.
    </p>
<example xml:id="ex-chi-square-GOF-intersections">
<title> Intersection Accidents</title> 
  <statement>
<p> State the null and alternative hypotheses, verify the assumption for a chi-square test, compute the test statistic, find the p-value, and state the conclusion in context.
</p> 
  </statement>
  <solution> <title> Hypotheses</title>
    <p>
      This is a chi-square goodness-of-fit test for a specific pattern. A random sample was taken and at least 5 accidents in each category.
    </p>
    <p> The hypotheses are: </p>
    <p> <m>H_0:</m> the population proportions are
      <m>0.20</m> for roundabouts,
      <m>0.30</m> for stop-sign intersections,
      <m>0.35</m> for traffic-light intersections,
      and <m>0.15</m> for other intersections,
      and </p>
    <p> <m>H_a:</m> the population accident distribution is different.
    </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title>Values</title>
    <p>
      Under the null hypothesis, the expected counts are the proportions multiplied by the sample size of <m>400</m>: Thus, we would expect
      <m>400(0.20)=80</m> in roundabouts,
      <m>400(0.30)=120</m> in stop-sign intersections,
      <m>400(0.35)=140</m> in traffic-light intersections,
      and
      <m>400(0.15)=60</m> in other intersections.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Observed and Expected Counts</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Intersection Type</cell>
          <cell>Observed</cell>
          <cell>Expected</cell>
          <cell><m>\dfrac{(O-E)^2}{E}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Roundabout</cell><cell>68</cell><cell>80</cell><cell><m>1.80</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Stop Sign</cell><cell>134</cell><cell>120</cell><cell><m>1.633</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Traffic Light</cell><cell>146</cell><cell>140</cell><cell><m>0.257</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Other</cell><cell>52</cell><cell>60</cell><cell><m>1.067</m></cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
</solution>
<solution> <title>Good Fit Test</title>
    <p>  The test statistic is
      <md>   \chi^2=\sum \frac{(O-E)^2}{E}=1.80+1.633+0.257+1.067=4.757
      </md>.   </p>
    <p> The degrees of freedom are <m>df=k-1=4-1=3</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Using a chi-square distribution with <m>3</m> degrees of freedom, the
      <m>p</m>-value is approximately <m>0.190</m>.
    </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> TI-84 GOF-test</title> 
<p>Press [STAT] button and under the EDIT menu select <term>1:Edit </term> and press [ENTER]. <term> Input</term> the Observed values in L1 and the Expected values in L2. </p>
<p> Press the STAT button and under the TESTS menu select <term>D: GOF-Test</term> and press [ENTER] to select it. Identify where the data is located and enter df=3 then press Calculate. </p>
<figure xml:id="ChiIntersect1">
            <caption>GOF-Test on calculator for Intersection Accidents</caption>
            <image source="ChiCars.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription> Test value chi=4.575 and p-value=0.190.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 
<p> The statistical test value is <m>\chi^2 = 4.757</m> and p-value =0.190</p>
</solution> 
<solution> <title>Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      Since <m>p=0.19 \gt 0.05</m>, we fail to reject <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is not sufficient evidence at the <m>0.05</m> significance level to
      conclude that the population distribution of accidents among roundabouts,
      stop-sign intersections, traffic-light intersections, and other types of
      intersections differs from the reported distribution.
    </p>
  </solution>




</example>



</subsection>


<subsection xml:id="subsec-GoodFitPractice">
  <title> Goodness of Fit Practice Problems </title>
<p> For each problem, state the null and alternative hypotheses, verify the assumption for a chi-square test, compute the test statistic, find the p-value, and state the conclusion in context. </p> 

<p> <term> Beetles</term> </p>
<p>
      A biologist is studying whether four color patterns of a certain beetle
      species occur in equal proportions in a forest habitat. After randomly
      collecting 160 beetles, the biologist records the following observed
      counts:
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Observed Beetle Color Pattern Counts</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Color Pattern</cell>
          <cell>Observed Count</cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Green</cell><cell>52</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Brown</cell><cell>33</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Striped</cell><cell>41</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Spotted</cell><cell>34</cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the four beetle color
      patterns are equally distributed in the population.
    </p>
<exercise xml:id="ex-chisquareGOF-equal-beetles">
<title> Beetles</title>
  <statement>
<p> State the null and alternative hypotheses, verify the assumption for a chi-square test, compute the test statistic, find the p-value, and state the conclusion in context.
</p> 
  </statement>
  <solution><title> Hypotheses</title>
    <p>
      The null hypothesis is that the four beetle color patterns are equally
      distributed in the population. So we would expect 25% in each category.
    </p>
    <p>
      The hypotheses are
      <m>H_0:p_1=p_2=p_3=p_4=0.25</m> or the color patterns are equally distributed
      and
      <m>H_a:</m> the color patterns are not equally distributed 
    </p>
</solution>
<solution><title> Values</title>
    <p>
      Since there are <m>160</m> beetles and <m>4</m> categories, the expected
      count for each category under equal distribution is  <m>\dfrac{160}{4}=40</m>.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Observed and Expected Counts</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Color Pattern</cell>
          <cell>Observed</cell>
          <cell>Expected</cell>
       <cell>Difference O=E</cell>
          <cell><m>\dfrac{(O-E)^2}{E}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Green</cell><cell>52</cell><cell>40</cell><cell>12</cell> <cell>3.60</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Brown</cell><cell>33</cell><cell>40</cell><cell>-7</cell> <cell><m>1.225</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Striped</cell><cell>41</cell><cell>40</cell><cell>1</cell> <cell><m>0.025</m></cell></row>
     <row><cell>Spotted</cell><cell>34</cell><cell>40</cell><cell>-6</cell> <cell><m>0.90</m></cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
</solution>
<solution><title> Good Fit Test</title> 
    <p> The chi-square test statistic is
      <md>   \chi^2=\sum \frac{(O-E)^2}{E}=3.60+1.225+0.025+0.90=5.75
      </md>.
    </p>
    <p> The degrees of freedom are <m>df=k-1=4-1=3</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Using a chi-square distribution with <m>3</m> degrees of freedom, the
      <m>p</m>-value is approximately <m>0.124</m>.
    </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> TI-84 GOF-test</title> 
<p>Press [STAT] button and under the EDIT menu select <term>1:Edit </term> and press [ENTER]. <term> Input</term> the Observed values in L1 and the Expected values in L2. </p>
<p> Press the STAT button and under the TESTS menu select <term>D: GOF-Test</term> and press [ENTER] to select it. Identify where the data is located and enter df=3 then press Calculate </p>
<p> The statistical test value is <m>\chi^2 = 5.75</m> and p-value =0.124</p>
<figure xml:id="ChiBeetles">
            <caption>GOF-Test on calculator for Beetles</caption>
            <image source="ChiBeetles.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription> Test value chi=5.75 and p-value=0.124</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 
</solution> 
<solution><title> Conclusion</title>
    <p>  Since <m>p=0.124 \gt 0.05</m>, we fail to reject <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is not sufficient evidence at the <m>0.05</m> significance level to
      conclude that the four beetle color patterns are not equally distributed
      in the population.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<p> <term> Support for Gun Laws</term> </p>
<p>
      A political scientist wants to test whether the distribution of opinions among United States senators matches a previously reported national distribution of stronger gun laws. In 2022 the Bipartisan Safer Communities Act passed for expanded background checks after several school shootings. A recent Gallup report suggested that among Americans, <m>60\%</m> support strong gun laws, <m>27\%</m> are neutral or keep as now,  and <m>13\%</m> oppose strong gun laws. To examine whether a current sample is consistent with that distribution, the researcher classifies a random sample of <m>100</m> senators and house representative with the following results.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Observed Opinions on Strong Gun Laws</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Opinion</cell>
          <cell>Observed Count</cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Support</cell><cell>55</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Neutral</cell><cell>24</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Oppose</cell><cell>21</cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the population
      distribution of opinions differs from the reported distribution.
    </p>

<exercise xml:id="ex-chisquareGOF-gun-laws">
<title> Gun Laws</title> 
  <statement>
<p> State the null and alternative hypotheses, verify the assumption for a chi-square test, compute the test statistic, find the p-value, and state the conclusion in context.
</p> 
  </statement>
  <solution> <title>Hypotheses</title>
    <p>
      This is a chi-square goodness-of-fit test looking at a specific pattern.
    </p>
    <p>
      The hypotheses are
      <m>H_0:</m> the population proportions are  <m>0.50</m>, <m>0.30</m>, and <m>0.20</m>  for support, neutral, and oppose, respectively,
      and
      <m>H_a:</m> the population distribution is different.
    </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title>Assumptions</title>
<p> A random sample was taken and at least 5 are in each category, thus the chi-square distribution is appropriate. </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title>Values</title>
    <p>
      Under <m>H_0</m>, the expected counts are found by multiplying each
      proportion by the sample size <m>100</m> senators.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Observed and Expected Counts</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Opinion</cell>
          <cell>Observed</cell>
          <cell>Expected</cell>
          <cell><m>\dfrac{(O-E)^2}{E}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Support</cell><cell>55</cell><cell>60</cell><cell><m>0.417</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Neutral</cell><cell>24</cell><cell>27</cell><cell><m>.333</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Oppose</cell><cell>21</cell><cell>13</cell><cell><m>4.923</m></cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
</solution>
<solution> <title>Good Fit Test</title>
    <p>  The test statistic is
      <md>    \chi^2=\sum \frac{(O-E)^2}{E}=0.417+0.333+4.923=5.67
      </md>.   </p>
    <p> The degrees of freedom are  <m>df=k-1=3-1=2</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Using a chi-square distribution with <m>2</m> degrees of freedom, the
      <m>p</m>-value is approximately <m>0.059</m>.
    </p>
    </solution>
  <solution> <title>Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      Since <m>p=0.059 \gt 0.05</m>, we fail to reject <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is not sufficient evidence at the <m>0.05</m> significance level to
      conclude that the population distribution of senators' opinions on strong
      gun laws differs from the reported distribution.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise> 

<p> <term> Fire Department Calls</term></p>
    <p>
      A city manager wants to test whether the distribution of calls received by
      the fire department matches a previously reported pattern. Past city data
      suggest that <m>15\%</m> of calls are for auto accidents, <m>10\%</m> are
      for fires, <m>45\%</m> are for medical emergencies, <m>20\%</m> are for
      public assistance, and <m>10\%</m> are for other calls. To investigate
      whether a more recent sample follows this distribution, the manager reviews
      <m>300</m> randomly selected fire department calls and classifies each one
      by type.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Observed Fire Department Call Types</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Call Type</cell>
          <cell>Observed Count</cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Auto Accidents</cell><cell>39</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Fires</cell><cell>36</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Medical Emergencies</cell><cell>126</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Public Assistance</cell><cell>63</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Other</cell><cell>36</cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the population
      distribution of fire department call types differs from the reported
      distribution.
    </p>

<exercise xml:id="ex-chi-square-gof-fire-department">
<title> Fire Department Calls</title>
  <statement>
<p> State the null and alternative hypotheses, verify the assumption for a chi-square test, compute the test statistic, find the p-value, and state the conclusion in context.
</p>
  </statement>
  <solution> <title> Hypotheses</title> 
    <p>
      This is a chi-square goodness-of-fit test for a specific pattern. A random sample of calls was taken and there are at least 5 in each category. 
    </p>
    <p> The hypotheses are </p>
     <p> <m>H_0:</m> the population proportions are
      <m>0.15</m> for auto accidents,
      <m>0.10</m> for fires,
      <m>0.45</m> for medical emergencies,
      <m>0.20</m> for public assistance,
      and <m>0.10</m> for other calls,
      and</p>
      <p> <m>H_a:</m> the population distribution is different.   </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title>Values</title>
    <p>
      Under the null hypotheses, the expected counts are the proportions multiplied by the sample size of <m>300</m>. Thus, we would expect
      <m>300(0.15)=45</m> auto accidents,
      <m>300(0.10)=30</m> fires,
      <m>300(0.45)=135</m> medical emergencies,
      <m>300(0.20)=60</m> public assistance,
      and
      <m>300(0.10)=30</m> other calls.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Observed and Expected Counts</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Call Type</cell>
          <cell>Observed</cell>
          <cell>Expected</cell>
          <cell><m>\dfrac{(O-E)^2}{E}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Auto Accidents</cell><cell>39</cell><cell>45</cell><cell><m>0.80</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Fires</cell><cell>36</cell><cell>30</cell><cell><m>1.20</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Medical Emergencies</cell><cell>126</cell><cell>135</cell><cell><m>0.60</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Public Assistance</cell><cell>63</cell><cell>60</cell><cell><m>0.15</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Other</cell><cell>36</cell><cell>30</cell><cell><m>1.20</m></cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
</solution>
<solution> <title>Good Fit Test</title>
    <p>  The test statistic is
      <md>    \chi^2=\sum \frac{(O-E)^2}{E}=0.80+1.20+0.60+0.15+1.20=3.95
      </md>.   </p>
    <p>  The degrees of freedom are  <m>df=k-1=5-1=4</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Using a chi-square distribution with <m>4</m> degrees of freedom, the
      <m>p</m>-value is approximately <m>0.413</m>.
    </p>
    </solution>
  <solution> <title>Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      Since <m>p=0.413 \gt 0.05</m>, we fail to reject <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is not sufficient evidence at the <m>0.05</m> significance level to
      conclude that the population distribution of fire department call types
      differs from the reported distribution.
    </p>
  </solution>




</exercise> 


 


</subsection>

</section> 
